<ns4445:section xmlns:ns4445="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.technologies.java.j2se.swing.developingSwingInterfaces.textComponents">
    <ns4446:title xmlns:ns4446="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Text Components</ns4446:title>
    <ns4447:para xmlns:ns4447="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Java supplies a very rich support for text components including a variety of editor kits
        (e.g. HTML editor kit). The class hierarchy for text components is shown below. </ns4447:para>
    <ns4448:figure xmlns:ns4448="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        <ns4449:title xmlns:ns4449="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Text Components</ns4449:title>
        <mediaobject xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xmlns="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><imageobject><imagedata fileref="TextComponents.jpg"/></imageobject></mediaobject>
    </ns4448:figure>    
    <ns4450:para xmlns:ns4450="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Text fields and text areas can handle plain text with the first being limited to single
        line text. Editor panes can handle styled text. All text components support unlimited
        undo/redo and customizable key maps and key bindings. Furthermore, like most of the swing
        class library, it subscribes to the model/view split, defining the components data
        representation (content) in a separate document class. </ns4450:para>
